The paper deals with memory-hard functions, which are primarily used in cryptography. Therefore, cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also introduces a new notion of sustained-memory complexity, which involves analyzing the memory usage of algorithms over many steps. This suggests that the paper could also be relevant to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Additionally, the paper involves constructing functions and analyzing their complexity, which could fall under cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
